<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-803-284  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 803 284.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  August 27 1990 v7 n35 p71(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Alan Huang: as head of optical computing at Bell Labs, Huangharnesses the power of light to solve communications problems.andO;(ATandamp;T Bell Laboratories) (Network Innovators)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Borsook, Paulina.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Alan Huang, head of the optical computing research and developmentprogram at AT and T's Bell Laboratories, is working on thecreation of the world's first functional optical computer.andP;  Heintroduced an optical computer in Jan, 1990, that utilizes lasersand lenses to carry out computing tasks.andP;  The light beams involvedin optical computing can intersect each other without loss ofdata, unlike electrons used in conventional computing.andP;  Huang seesfiber optics as the first step toward an optical computingrevolution, but thinks that the combination of photonic andelectronic modes now in evidence is too inefficient, and that moreemphasis needs to be placed on optical research.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   AT and T Bell Laboratories Inc. (research).andO;Topic:     Research and DevelopmentOptical ComputersLaser and Infrared CommunicationFuture of ComputingPhotonics.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Alan Huang. (portrait)Person:    Huang, Alan (research).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>